ave responded to terrorist threats, climate change, and natural hazards, Coaffee shows how and why these measures have proven inadequate and what should be done to make us more resilient. While conventional approaches have focused on planning and preparing for disruptions and enhanced our ability to ";bounce back,"; our focus should be on anticipating future challenges and enhancing our capacity to adapt to new threats.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEmergency management. 0aHazard mitigation. 0aOrganizational resilience. 0aUncertainty. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disasters & Disaster Relief.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065488240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300244953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300244953.jpg  a978-3-11-061013-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065488-2  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2019  aZDB-23-DSWb2019